.TH "IAM-UPDATE-ASSUME-ROLE-POLICY" "a" "" ""
.SH NAME
iam-update-assume-role-policy \- Updates the policy that grants an IAM entity permission to assume a role
.SH DESCRIPTION
.sp
Updates the policy that grants an IAM entity permission to assume a role. This is typically referred to as the "role trust policy". For more information about roles, see \fI\%Using roles to delegate permissions and federate identities\fP .
.sp
See also: AWS API Documentation
.sp
See \(aqaws help\(aq for descriptions of global parameters.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
  update\-assume\-role\-policy
\-\-role\-name <value>
\-\-policy\-document <value>
[\-\-cli\-input\-json | \-\-cli\-input\-yaml]
[\-\-generate\-cli\-skeleton <value>]
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SH OPTIONS
.sp
\fB\-\-role\-name\fP (string)
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
The name of the role to update with the new policy.
.sp
This parameter allows (through its \fI\%regex pattern\fP ) a string of characters consisting of upper and lowercase alphanumeric characters with no spaces. You can also include any of the following characters: _+=,.@\-
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fB\-\-policy\-document\fP (string)
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
The policy that grants an entity permission to assume the role.
.sp
You must provide policies in JSON format in IAM. However, for AWS CloudFormation templates formatted in YAML, you can provide the policy in JSON or YAML format. AWS CloudFormation always converts a YAML policy to JSON format before submitting it to IAM.
.sp
The \fI\%regex pattern\fP used to validate this parameter is a string of characters consisting of the following:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
Any printable ASCII character ranging from the space character (\fB\eu0020\fP ) through the end of the ASCII character range
.IP \(bu 2
The printable characters in the Basic Latin and Latin\-1 Supplement character set (through \fB\eu00FF\fP )
.IP \(bu 2
The special characters tab (\fB\eu0009\fP ), line feed (\fB\eu000A\fP ), and carriage return (\fB\eu000D\fP )
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fB\-\-cli\-input\-json\fP | \fB\-\-cli\-input\-yaml\fP (string)
Reads arguments from the JSON string provided. The JSON string follows the format provided by \fB\-\-generate\-cli\-skeleton\fP\&. If other arguments are provided on the command line, those values will override the JSON\-provided values. It is not possible to pass arbitrary binary values using a JSON\-provided value as the string will be taken literally. This may not be specified along with \fB\-\-cli\-input\-yaml\fP\&.
.sp
\fB\-\-generate\-cli\-skeleton\fP (string)
Prints a JSON skeleton to standard output without sending an API request. If provided with no value or the value \fBinput\fP, prints a sample input JSON that can be used as an argument for \fB\-\-cli\-input\-json\fP\&. Similarly, if provided \fByaml\-input\fP it will print a sample input YAML that can be used with \fB\-\-cli\-input\-yaml\fP\&. If provided with the value \fBoutput\fP, it validates the command inputs and returns a sample output JSON for that command.
.sp
See \(aqaws help\(aq for descriptions of global parameters.
.SH EXAMPLES
.sp
\fBTo update the trust policy for an IAM role\fP
.sp
The following \fBupdate\-assume\-role\-policy\fP command updates the trust policy for the role named \fBTest\-Role\fP:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
aws iam update\-assume\-role\-policy \-\-role\-name Test\-Role \-\-policy\-document file://Test\-Role\-Trust\-Policy.json
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
The trust policy is defined as a JSON document in the \fITest\-Role\-Trust\-Policy.json\fP file. (The file name and extension
do not have significance.) The trust policy must specify a principal.
.sp
To update the permissions policy for a role, use the \fBput\-role\-policy\fP command.
.sp
For more information, see \fI\%Creating a Role\fP in the \fIUsing IAM\fP guide.
.SH OUTPUT
.sp
None
